<p>Did man directly evolve from apes?  May be, looks that way, certainly could have.  Is it possible that there is another potential origin?  Yep.  Do any of them have the basis of a theory that evolution does?  Nope.  Doesn&#8217;t mean they are not possible though, just less probable.</p>
<p>For all we know we are fricken star children, that ancient aliens are real!  Of course I would simply say well, that isn&#8217;t an answer, how did they get us here and where did they come from.</p>
<p>I actually don&#8217;t believe in an origin of the universe by the way.  (if we define the universe as everything that is, multiple universes then would just be more universe, known vs. unknown).  </p>
<p>What I believe in I call the theory of existence.  All that is has always been, only the arrangement and assemblages have changed.  The &#8220;big bang&#8221; is likely just part of a contraction and expansion cycle and time has no real meaning at the cosmic scale.  </p>
<p>I wrote a paper on this by the way in NINETH GRADE, I called it &#8220;Religious Misconceptions and Scientific Jokes&#8221;.  I got a D!  I was told I deserved an F but since the paper was long enough and met the technical requirements I got a D instead.  </p>
<p>Today much of this is now cutting edge theoretical theory.  </p>
<p>I had this same teacher in 10th grade, she could not understand why I simply didn&#8217;t do my term paper that year at all.  In her class I got three As and one C.  The C came in the quarter that the term paper was due as it counted as a test grade and drug down all my As.</p>
<p>When I simply explained that it wasn&#8217;t worth my time and three As and one C equaled a final average of an A, and that was all that would be on my record, she rolled her eyes and we sort of had a live and let live relationship after that.  </p>
<p>She was shocked when I took two scientific electives with here in my final years!  One day she asked me why I would do that,  I told her I liked science and that she was usually right about it and a good teacher.  </p>
<p>She who gave my paper a D a paper that likely should have been showcased for independent study, ended up one of my favorite teachers.</p>
