		<div class="comment-body"><p>@Scott, I am glad that you are able to distill the unknowns of cosmology down to a simple &#8220;you are wrong&#8221; answer.  You said, &#8220;you don’t have to look far to see that time shows up again and again in the calculus of the cosmos&#8221;.</p>
<p>Odd, I didn&#8217;t know the cosmos required us to calculate it!</p>
<p>Just because there are constants in the universe, such as at least our understanding of lights &#8220;speed&#8221; doesn&#8217;t make time real.  To me I consider it simply a variable we created for our convenience so that we might try to understand the world and universe better.  Again in my view time is a human construct simply created by humans to explain something only humans (as far as we know) can conceive of, how &#8220;long&#8221; some event takes.  </p>
<p>Why do we care about this?  One real reason, we are mortal.  As such we both die and we have phyical limitations to movement and travel and we &#8220;feel&#8221; pain and discomfort.  Remove those and not only does time become meaningless but in effect so does space.</p>
<p>What people like me are saying isn&#8217;t that time in and of itself doesn&#8217;t exist, it does in a way, simply because we will it so.  More that time and space are not the separate things that man has them divided into.  Neither space or time really exist, but &#8220;space-time&#8221; is real.  In much the same way man with his limited understanding has tried to separate matter and energy.  This make no real sense to me at all.  I feel all energy is matter and all matter is energy.  Not just convertible to each other but that they are one in the same, simply manifest differently based on current assemblage.  </p>
<p>Your flat earther comment is both rude and one made in ignorance.  Not only are there top physicists in the world right now that agree with the summation of the non existence of time.  I mean that is just those who agree with me.  So how about the words of Julian Barbour, &#8220;time is the one thing we can most accurately measure as physicists, but we can&#8217;t even agree on what it is&#8221;.  So not only do some of the brightest minds in the world agree with me, those that don&#8217;t can&#8217;t even agree with each other about what time is.</p>
<p>A man that mocks what he doesn&#8217;t understand is usually afraid of what he doesn&#8217;t understand being true.</p>
